'''Postpartum chills''' is a [[Physiology | physiological response]] that occurs within two hours of [[childbirth]]. It appears as uncontrollable [[shivering]]. It is seen in many women after delivery and can be unpleasant. It lasts for a short time. It is thought to be a result of a nervous system response. It may also be related to [[fluid shift]]s and the actual strenuous work of labor. It is considered a normal response and there is no accompanying [[fever]]. A fever would indicate an [[postpartum infections|infection]]. Reassurance is all that is needed and for the mother to be kept warm. It has been described as a fairly common and normal occurrence.<ref name="RavidGidoni">{{cite journal|last1=Ravid|first1=Dorit|last2=Gidoni|first2=Yariv|last3=Bruchim|first3=Ilan|last4=Shapira|first4=Hava|last5=Fejgin|first5=Moshe|title=Postpartum chills phenomenon: Is it a feto-maternal transfusion reaction?|journal=Acta Obstetricia et Gynecologica Scandinavica|volume=80|issue=2|year=2001|pages=149–151|issn=0001-6349|doi=10.1034/j.1600-0412.2001.080002149.x}}</ref><!--still looking for non-primary source--><ref>http://www.webmd.com/baby/tc/labor-delivery-and-postpartum-period-after-childbirth</ref> It is thought to be possibly related to the environmental temperature.<ref name="Harper">{{cite journal |last1=Harper |first1=RG |last2=Quintin |first2=A |last3=Kreynin |first3=I |last4=Brooks |first4=GZ |last5=Farahani |first5=G |last6=Lesser |first6=M |title=Observations on the postpartum shivering phenomenon. |journal=The Journal of reproductive medicine |date=November 1991 |volume=36 |issue=11 |pages=803-7 |pmid=1765959}}</ref>

