{{for|other uses of the word "skeletonization"|Skeletonization (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Example_of_a_pig_carcass_in_the_dry_decay_stage_of_decomposition.jpg|thumb|right|Partly skeletonized [[Domestic pig|pig]], seven weeks after death.]]
{{Signs of death}}
'''Skeletonization''' refers to the final stage of [[Decomposition#Dry/remains|decomposition]], during which the last vestiges of the [[Tissue (biology)|soft tissues]] of a [[Cadaver|corpse]] or [[Carrion|carcass]] have decayed or dried to the point that the [[skeleton]] is exposed. By the end of the skeletonization process, all soft tissue will have been eliminated, leaving only disarticulated bones.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Tersigni-Tarrant |first1=MariaTeresa A. |last2=Shirley |first2=Natalie R. |date=2012 |title=Forensic Anthropology: An Introduction |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CHU1Kf0CjVQC |location= |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |pages=351 |isbn=9781439816462 |accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In a [[temperate]] [[climate]], it usually requires three weeks to several years for a body to completely decompose into a skeleton, depending on factors such as temperature, humidity, presence of insects, and submergence in a [[substrate (materials science)|substrate]] such as water.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Senn |first1=David R. |last2=Weems |first2=Richard A. |date=2013 |title=Manual of Forensic Odontology, Fifth Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c9u0MUnexdIC |location= |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |pages=48 |isbn=9781439851333 |accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref> In tropical climates, skeletonization can occur in weeks, while in [[tundra]] areas, skeletonization may take years or may never occur, if subzero temperatures persist. Natural [[embalming]] processes in [[peat bog]]s or salt [[desert]]s can delay the process indefinitely, sometimes resulting in [[Mummy#Natural mummification|natural mummification]].<ref name="Byrd">{{cite book |last1=Byrd |first1=Jason H. |last2=Castner |first2=James L. |date=2012 |title=Forensic Entomology: The Utility of Arthropods in Legal Investigations, Second Edition |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HFG6qQeCY-8C |location= |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |pages=407–423 |isbn=9781420008869 |accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref>

The rate of skeletonization and the present condition of a corpse or carcass can be used to determine the time of death.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dix |first1=Jay |last2=Graham |first2=Michael |date=1999 |title=Time of Death, Decomposition and Identification: An Atlas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qxO3Z0um6WMC |location= |publisher=[[CRC Press]] |pages=11–12 |isbn=9780849323676 |accessdate=March 11, 2014}}</ref>

After skeletonization, if scavenging animals do not destroy or remove the bones, acids in many fertile [[soil]]s take about 20 years to completely dissolve the skeleton of mid- to large-size mammals, such as humans, leaving no trace of the organism. In [[pH|neutral-pH]] soil or sand, the skeleton can persist for hundreds of years before it finally disintegrates. Alternately, especially in very fine, dry, salty, anoxic, or mildly alkaline soils, bones may undergo [[fossil]]ization, converting into minerals that may persist indefinitely.<ref name="Byrd"/> 
